five sample summaries

[1] Over the long course of human history, malaria is the infectious disease that has killed more humans than any other malaria. It is carried in the bites of infected mosquitos, and it is probably our oldest scourge. There were 300 million cases of malaria and half of which died. Treatment has been known for centuries since the 1600s. It used to be caused by bad air called miasma, but malaria was found to be carried by mosquitoes, and in 1897, a malaria prevention method was established. Malaria is a fourth cause, combined with three. It is scientific, economic, historical, and political. Economic and cultural factors have a lot to do with why malaria cannot be eradicated. Many malaria infected areas have no facilities to store doctors or drugs because of lack of infrastructure. Also, because malaria is common to people in the region, few people try to prevent it. Fighting malaria producing lifestyles is the only way forward.
[2] Over the long course of human history, the infectious disease that's killed more humans than any other is malaria. Malaria should be a relatively simple disease to solve, and yet to this day, hundreds of thousands of people are going to die from the bite of a mosquito. She thinks there are three reasons for the spread of malaria. The first reason is certainly scientific. It would be better if we avoided places where mosquitoes live, but we are creating the places that mosquitoes like to live. There’s a huge scientific challenge, but there’s a huge economic challenge too. One economist said if you have malaria in your society, your economic growth is depressed. There is also a cultural challenge. People think it’s normal to have malaria. That adds up to the biggest problem of all which is a political problem.                                                                                                                     
[3]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         
[4] In the long history of mankind, the infectious disease that caused the most deaths was malaria.A disease contracted by the bite of an infected mosquito.Malaria is the most devastating epidemic in human history, still affecting 300 million people and killing over 500,000 annually. It’s an outrageous reality because a cure, using quinine from the cinchona bark, was discovered in the 1600s. The speaker , a Jain-raised journalist, shared her personal struggle with mosquitoes during childhood visits to India. Her five-year investigation into why malaria persists identifies three primary factors.First, The biological agent that causes the disease. Second, poor living conditions that increase mosquito exposure. Third, the overall social structure and environment that perpetuates the disease.                                                                                                                                             
[5] In human history, malaria has killed a lot of people, and now, a lot of people have died from the mosquito carrying the virus “Malaria”. Malaria should be a relatively simple disease to solve, but a lot of people still died by the mosquito. She thinks that it has 3 main reasons. This little parasite causes malaria and it poses the more complex for human kind. If you avoid the mosquito’s life, it will be difficult to do it because they can live even in the rain. If you are poor, you can not avoid the mosquito carrying the malaria because you have to harvest your product from your field. Insects do their best to survive and the human body does their best to find it. The insects do their best to survive and spread the virus. We will be able to decrease 1.3 % for a year. We have to do our best to decrease the number of people suffering from malaria. It takes money, time, training, resources, infrastructure, and many more.
